      <!-- INTRO -->
      <section id="intro" style="padding: 0; margin-bottom: 3rem;">
        <p>
          Riyadh, the sprawling capital of the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia, stands today as a monumental entity of contrast. It is a metropolis where ancient Najdi clay-brick heritage coexists seamlessly with the most ambitious, hyper-futuristic engineering projects of Saudi Vision 2030. In Riyadh, the past is not forgotten; rather, it forms the foundation upon which a global city of the future is being built. As you walk through its districts, you transition from the historic birthplace of the first Saudi state in Diriyah to the towering steel-and-glass skyscrapers of the King Abdullah Financial District (KAFD). This architectural and sociological duality makes the city one of the most compelling destinations in the Middle East.
        </p>
        <p>
          Historically known as <em>Hajr al-Yamamah</em>, a fertile valley settlement that lay along trade routes across the Arabian Peninsula, Riyadh has evolved from an isolated desert oasis into a thriving G20 capital. Today, the city is a financial and political powerhouse, home to over seven million residents. Its geographical location in the Najd region—a vast sedimentary plateau in the center of the peninsula—has shaped its architecture, its culture, and its climate. Riyadh experiences a desert climate characterized by hot summers and cool, crisp winter nights, making the cooler months a magical time to explore the city. The dry air of the plateau prevents the humidity experienced on the coasts, rendering even warmer autumn days pleasant under the shade of palm groves.
        </p>
        <p>
          Riyadh's transformation has entered a dramatic new chapter as the city prepares to serve as the primary host for the **FIFA World Cup 2034**. This mega-event is accelerating the city's infrastructure, cultural projects, and transportation systems, transforming Riyadh into an accessible, open, and world-class tourist destination. Millions of fans will walk through its state-of-the-art transit stations, gather in its expansive fan zones, and sit in stadiums that showcase the cutting edge of sports architecture. Whether you are a business traveler, a heritage enthusiast, a football fan, or a luxury seeker, Riyadh offers an array of experiences that showcase the legendary warmth of Saudi hospitality (<em>Dafah</em>).
        </p>
        <p>
          As we look towards 2026 and beyond, the city's master plan is rapidly unfolding. Massive projects like the Green Riyadh Initiative are planting millions of trees across the urban canopy, reducing temperatures and creating pedestrian corridors. Meanwhile, the construction of the King Salman Park—set to be the largest urban park in the world—will introduce extensive green lakes, sports academies, and cultural theaters to the center of the capital. This guide provides an exhaustive, expert breakdown of Riyadh's history, sports venues, transport networks, accommodations, and culinary secrets to help you navigate this dynamic metropolis.
        </p>

